The Week In Crypto Policy: Debanking & Innovation

George Leonardo

Dec 6, 2024 ⋅  11 min read

Key Takeaways

  • The House Financial Services committee held a hearing exploring how innovations in AI, crypto, and startup fundraising can benefit all Americans, including substantive discussions of stablecoins and Operation Choke Point 2.0.
  • With an increasing number of crypto and tech entrepreneurs going public with stories of getting debanked, Democrat and Republican lawmakers are calling for further investigation into whether banking regulators have pushed banks to limit or avoid doing business with companies in politically disfavored industries.
  • President-elect Trump nominated Paul Atkins—a former SEC Commissioner, supporter of light-touch regulation, and crypto ally—to serve as the next SEC Chair.
  • President-elect Trump appointed tech entrepreneur and investor David Sacks to serve as the first ever White House AI and Crypto Czar and lead the Presidential Council of Advisors for Science and Technology.

HFSC Hearing on Innovation

On Wednesday, the House Financial Services committee held a hearing entitled: Innovation Revolution: How Technology is Shaping the Future of Finance.

Chair Patrick McHenry’s (R-NC) last hearing featured Republicans and Democrats exploring how policymakers can boost innovation in America, and how innovations in AI, crypto, and startup fundraising can benefit all Americans.

Members made sure to wish Chair McHenry well, praising the outgoing chairman for his bipartisan leadership, with many specifically highlighting his work on digital assets (and even more sporting his iconic bowtie as a tribute).

Here’s a closer look at crypto-specific discussions.

Stablecoins

Democrats and Republicans often focused questions on the potential benefits innovation could have on the average American, historically underserved populations, and small businesses.

  • Responding to various questions along these lines, Denelle Dixon (CEO of Stellar Development Foundation) highlighted how stablecoins allow individuals and small businesses to transfer value faster and cheaper than traditional payment methods, particularly when it comes to cross border transfers and/or where individuals lack access to a bank account.
  • Dixon and Nathan McCauley (CEO of Anchorage Digital) also discussed stablecoins’ potential to boost demand for the U.S. dollar because the overwhelming majority of stablecoins used today are $USD-denominated.

Rep. Gregory Meeks (D-NY) emphasized the importance of ensuring any stablecoin legislation includes a viable state pathway for issuers and minimum federal floor requirements.

  • McCauley strongly agreed with this sentiment, describing the shared responsibilities of federal and state bank regulators as one of the “great traditions” of American financial regulation.

Rep. Nydia Velazquez (D-NY) raised concerns about allowing nonbank commercial firms to engage in bank-like financial services (i.e., issuing stablecoins).

  • Dixon responded that she believes current legislative proposals adequately address these concerns by requiring issuers to maintain 1:1 backing of reserves (i.e., prohibit issuers from engaging in bank-like fractional reserve lending).

Ranking Member Maxine Waters (D-CA) quipped in her opening statement that she hoped Chair McHenry could “pull a rabbit out of his hat” on a stablecoin compromise in the coming weeks, but the general sentiment across the board was that stablecoins and market structure legislation are likely tabled until the 119th Congress.

Choke Point 2.0

Rep. French Hill (R-AR) once again made clear that he plans to get to the bottom of Operation Choke Point 2.0. Rep. Hill opened his questioning by asking witnesses if they had been debanked.

  • Dixon and McCauley said their companies had been debanked.
  • Dixon said Stellar has had to go to 10 different banks, and was cut off from the bank they had used during their first six years, without being given a reason.
  • McCauley said Anchorage was debanked shortly after banking regulators issued their joint statement on “Crypto-Asset Risks to Banking Organizations” in January 2023. The bank told them it was because Anchorage was a crypto business.

Rep. Hill added he’s concerned the FDIC may have pressured banks verbally (rather than in writing) to avoid FOIA.

See full exchange via Rep. Hill's X post here.

Rep. Wiley Nickel (D-NC) (retiring) also brought up risks of debanking, asking how it could impact innovation.

  • McCauley responded that debanking leads to concentration risks and has led many of Anchorage’s clients to distrust U.S. financial regulators, ultimately driving talent and businesses overseas.

Illicit Finance

Rep. Bryan Steil (R-WI) asked for suggestions on how Congress should address illicit finance concerns involving digital assets.

  • Dixon replied that, given the transparency inherent in blockchain technology, the focus should be on leveraging tools available to combat illicit finance before adding new rules.

Regulators

Rep. Mike Flood (R-NE) asked how regulators could better keep up with rapidly changing fields like crypto.

  • McCauley suggested one option could be to allow agency employees to own at least small amounts of crypto to better understand what they are seeking to regulate.

Lawmakers Respond to Debanking Claims

Background

Operation Choke Point 2.0 is receiving increased attention from lawmakers after a16z cofounder Marc Andreessen discussed the debanking of crypto and tech firms on the Joe Rogan Podcast.

While Congress (see, e.g., Senator Hagerty letter from March 2023), industry groups, and venture capital investor Nic Carter, have been sounding the alarm on crypto’s banking issues for almost two years, Andreessen’s comments on Rogan appear to have elevated the issue on both sides of the aisle, as an increasing number of founders and operators have come public with their stories of getting debanked.

Lawmakers React

Here's a quick look at how some Members of Congress responded over the last week.

​Senator Kevin Cramer, who sponsors the Fair Access to Banking Act (briefly summarized below) reposted the clip of Andreessen's comments, adding:

What Can Congress Do About OCP 2.0?

Oversight

​Congress could use its oversight authority to investigate the extent to which banking regulators pressured banks to limit or avoid doing business with politically disfavored groups. For example, committees could hold hearings and request documents and information from agencies to better understand if there were any violations of current law, and how the law could be amended to make sure political debanking doesn't happen again.

Legislation

There are two main bills that broadly aim to ensure fair access to banking services for all businesses, beyond just crypto and tech: (1) the Fair Access to Banking Act and (2) the SAFER Banking Act (§ 10).

(1) Fair Access to Banking Act

​The Fair Access to Banking Act would prohibit banks from denying a customer service unless the denial was justified by quantitative, impartial, risk-based standards established in advance by the bank and the customer was given written notice. See § 8(b). Banks that fail to follow to the law’s requirements would lose access to the federal reserve’s discount window lending program and FDIC deposit insurance (among other potential penalties). See § 4.

Rep. Andy Barr (R-KY), who is running for House Financial Services Chair next year, is the lead sponsor of the House's Fair Access to Banking Act. This bill has 126 cosponsors but failed to advance out of Committee this year.

Senator Kevin Cramer (R-ND) is the lead sponsor of companion legislation in the Senate. The Senate bill has 36 cosponsors and remains stalled in Senate Banking.

While unlikely to pass this year, the Fair Access to Banking Act would likely serve as a key foundation for future proposals related to ending the practice of regulators pressuring banks to debank certain customers or groups of customers.

(2) Section 10 of SAFER Banking Act

​Section 10 of the SAFER Banking Act (“SAFER”) includes language aimed at preventing regulators from requesting or requiring a bank to terminate customer accounts without a valid reason—though it would still leave regulators broad discretion. For example, a “valid reason” could include that the regulator has reasonable cause to believe a bank is engaged in or “about to engage in” any “activity…that could lead to…the issuance of a matter requiring attention.” See SAFER Banking Act §10(b)(2)(A).

​Senate Banking passed SAFER out of committee by a 14-9 vote on September 27, 2023. It's unclear whether SAFER, which is supported by Senator Majority Leader Chuck Schumer, will make it into an end of year bill and whether it would include Section 10 as passed out of committee.

Looking for more on OCP 2.0?

Look Ahead

2024

  • Eyes out to see if any crypto-related provisions get added to the NDAA or a government funding bill.
  • Also eyes out to see if regulators finalize any new rules (see, e.g., non-custodial digital asset broker reporting rules discussed below).

Quick Hits

Tax: Non-Custodial Digital Asset Broker Reporting Rules

  • ​Treasury is reportedly still planning to finalize tax reporting requirements for non-custodial digital asset ​brokers by year end.
    • If Treasury does indeed finalize the rule, Congress could repeal it via a Congressional Review Act resolution of disapproval next year, which only requires a simple majority vote in the House & Senate, and would also have the effect of prohibiting Treasury from finalizing any substantially similar rule in the future.
    • Congress could also pass legislation to narrow or clarify the scope of any final rule, rather than rescind it in its entirety (see, e.g., the Keep Innovation America Act (bipartisan)).
    • Recall, Treasury and the IRS finalized tax reporting rules for custodial brokers of digital assets in June of this year, but said it was still working through rules for non-custodial brokers.

SEC

  • President-elect Trump nominated former SEC Commissioner Paul Atkins to serve as the next SEC Chair.
    • In a Truth Social post announcing the nomination, Trump specifically mentioned Atkins' pro-digital assets views:
  • As further background, Atkins served as SEC Commissioner from 2002-2008, is on the Board of Advisors of The Digital Chamber and has been advising digital asset firms as the founder and CEO of his own consulting firm, Patomak Global Partners.
  • ​In an Op-Ed for the American Banker on stablecoins in 2022, Atkins urged Congress to avoid “a sweeping, one-size-fits-all solution that undermines the innovation and dynamism that make America’s financial services sector so vibrant.”
  • For more detailed background on Atkins, here's a helpful thread from Greg Xethalis, GC at Multicoin Capital, here.

Crypto Tsar

  • President-elect Trump appointed tech entrepreneur and investor David Sacks to serve as the first “White House AI & Crypto Czar” and to lead the Presidential Council of Advisors for Science and Technology.

AML

Tornado Cash

  • In a case brought by plaintiffs who used Tornado Cash for legitimate privacy-seeking purposes, the Fifth Circuit held:
    • “Tornado Cash’s immutable smart contracts (the lines of privacy-enabling software code) are not the “property” of a foreign national or entity, meaning (1) they cannot be blocked under IEEPA, and (2) OFAC overstepped its congressionally defined authority.”
    • The court added: “OFAC’s concerns with illicit foreign actors laundering funds are undeniably legitimate[,]” but it's up to Congress to update IEEPA.
    • ​Text of Opinion.

Criminal Liability Under 8 U.S.C. § 1960

  • In a new paper for the The International Academy of Financial Crime Litigators, Amanda Tuminelli (DeFi Education Fund), Jake Chervinsky (Variant), and Daniel Barabander (Variant) dive deep into when criminal liability should properly arise under 8 U.S.C. § 1960—the statute criminalizing the operation of an unlicensed money transmitting business at the center of the Tornado Cash and Samurai Wallet cases.
    • The authors argue Section 1960 requires that the defendant both obtain control of funds and reliquinqish control of funds, and have knowledge that the money transmitting business must be licensed.
    • Full Paper: “Through the Looking Glass: Conceptualizing Control and Analyzing Criminal Liability For Unlicensed Money Transmitting Businesses Under Section 1960”

Federal Reserve

  • Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell says “Bitcoin is not a competitor for the dollar, it’s really a competitor for gold.” (Logan Hitchcock, Decrypt).
